answer:
1. Cut the four upper fingers of the latex glove so that the thumb remains intact.
2. Cut a 30cm piece of silicone tube (see FASE 1);
3. Take the glove just cut and insert it on the 250ml beaker using a piece of paper tape to ensure a tight fit. Then insert the silicone tube into the glove and secure it with a plastic clip (see FASE 2);
4. Insert the free end of the silicone tube into the U-shaped drying tube. Also in this case secure everything with a piece of paper tape (see FASE 3);
5. Position the pliers and the plastic base so that you can support the 100ml beaker in one of the two pliers, then place the U-shaped drying tube inside it and close its free end with the rubber stopper (see FASE 4);
6. Move back to the 250ml beaker and cut the thumb from the tip. Use the scissors to cut the latex glove into small pieces and place them in the beaker. Add 100ml of water and 100ml of alcohol to the beaker. Stir the mixture with the plastic stick until the latex pieces are completely dissolved (see FASE 5);
7. Place the beaker on the tripod and heat it with the Bunsen burner. When the temperature reaches 65°C, the alcohol will begin to evaporate and flow through the silicone tube to the U-shaped drying tube where it will condense due to the surface cooled by the ice in the beaker. During the entire extraction of alcohol, the temperature measured with the thermometer will remain constant, its increase will therefore indicate the end of the alcohol in the mixture.
